spanishExample: A veces nos dan unas cosas.
englishTranslation: Sometimes they give us some things.
vocabIncluded: nos: "us" as an indirect object ("to us", "for us")

spanishExample: Antes de su vuelta, tienes que darme eso.
englishTranslation: Before her return, you have to give me that.
vocabIncluded: using Tener with "que" to indicate obligation

spanishExample: Aún no me has dado *the answer* a mi pregunta.
englishTranslation: You haven’t yet given me the answer to my question.
vocabIncluded: a: complement (e.g. ayudar a, empezar a) (preposition)
has: "have", "you have" before a participle (Haber, present, 2nd person)
me: "me" as an indirect object ("to me", "for me")

spanishExample: Ayer estaban dando *candies* en *the street.*
englishTranslation: Yesterday, they were giving candies on the street.

spanishExample: Damos una vuelta sin tu ayuda.
englishTranslation: We’re taking a walk without your help.

spanishExample: Está de vuelta, así que podemos dar una vuelta.
englishTranslation: She is present again, so we can take a walk.

spanishExample: Le doy esto hoy.
englishTranslation: I’m giving him this today.
vocabIncluded: le: "her/him" as an indirect object ("to her/him", "for her/him")

spanishExample: Le tienes que dar la cosa antes de la fiesta.
englishTranslation: You have to give him the thing before the party.
vocabIncluded: le: "her/him" as an indirect object ("to her/him", "for her/him")
using Tener with "que" to indicate obligation

spanishExample: Les tienes que dar eso de nuevo.
englishTranslation: You have to give them that anew.
vocabIncluded: les: "them" as an indirect object ("to them", "for them")
using Tener with "que" to indicate obligation

spanishExample: Mañana se lo va a dar a alguien más.
englishTranslation: Tomorrow he’s going to give it to someone else.
vocabIncluded: "se" to mean "le" or "les", as in "se lo" or "se la"
a, used in a "redundant indirect object", e.g. le hice un favor a la chica
using Ir and "a" to put verbs in the future (e.g. "voy a ser")

spanishExample: No dan as much money como él da.
englishTranslation: They don’t give as much money as he gives.

spanishExample: No me das lo mismo que ella me da.
englishTranslation: You don’t give me the same that she gives me.
vocabIncluded: me da lo mismo: "it's all the same to me" (idiom)
me: "me" as an indirect object ("to me", "for me")

spanishExample: No me lo tienes que dar; me da lo mismo.
englishTranslation: You don’t have to give it to me; it’s all the same to me.
vocabIncluded: me da lo mismo: "it's all the same to me" (idiom)
me: "me" as an indirect object ("to me", "for me")
using Tener with "que" to indicate obligation

spanishExample: Nunca les damos nada, pero tú sí les das algo.
englishTranslation: We never give them anything, but you do give them something.
vocabIncluded: les: "them" as an indirect object ("to them", "for them")
sí: adverb meaning "indeed" or otherwise providing positive emphasis

spanishExample: Para entonces, se lo habrá dado.
englishTranslation: By then, he will have given it to her.
vocabIncluded: "se" to mean "le" or "les", as in "se lo" or "se la"
habrá: "will have", "he/she/it will have" before a participle (Haber, future, 3rd person)

spanishExample: Podemos hacerlo de esta manera; me da lo mismo.
englishTranslation: We can do it in this manner; it’s all the same to me.
vocabIncluded: me da lo mismo: "it's all the same to me" (idiom)

spanishExample: Si me das lo que ella te ha dado, te diré el camino.
englishTranslation: If you give me what she has given you, I’ll tell you the path.
vocabIncluded: "lo que": "what" as a connector between phrases
diré: "will say", "I will say" (Decir, future, 1st person)
ha: "has", "he/she/it has" before a participle (Haber, present, 3rd person)
me: "me" as an indirect object ("to me", "for me")
te: "you" as an indirect object ("to you", "for you")

spanishExample: Si se lo da luego, me da lo mismo.
englishTranslation: If he gives it to her later, it’s all the same to me.
vocabIncluded: "se" to mean "le" or "les", as in "se lo" or "se la"
me da lo mismo: "it's all the same to me" (idiom)

spanishExample: Siempre das todo lo que tienes, pero ellos no dan nada.
englishTranslation: You always give everything you have, but they don’t give anything.

spanishExample: Te doy una oportunidad, entonces no *arrive* tarde.
englishTranslation: I’m giving you an opportunity, so don’t arrive late.
vocabIncluded: te: "you" as an indirect object ("to you", "for you")

spanishExample: Tienes que hacerle caso porque te está dando *good advice.*
englishTranslation: You have to pay attention to him because he is giving you good advice.
vocabIncluded: te: "you" as an indirect object ("to you", "for you")
using Tener with "que" to indicate obligation

spanishExample: Todavía no das una vuelta.
englishTranslation: You still aren’t taking a walk.
